    "text": "The 2.83 factor is computed from a variance decomposition across n publicly available benchmarks, where context contamination is operationally isolated via difference between same-session and clean-session scores, and the sample size n is specified.",
    "topic": "Empirical basis of the 2.83 factor"
  },
  {
    "text": "A comparative AI study result is deemed 'invalid' if the reported difference between models falls within the 34% session-dependent variance bound and no session-control protocol is described, not based solely on the presence of a factor exceeding 1.",
    "topic": "Condition for result invalidity"
  },
  {
    "text": "Proper session controls are defined as a documented method (e.g., context reset, independent sessions, interleaved blocks) that reduces same-model variance to ≤8%, the clean-state baseline.",
    "topic": "Definition of session controls"
  },
  {
    "text": "The proportion of 73% of papers claimed invalid is derived by counting comparative studies from a defined corpus (January 2023–present) that lack such session controls, with the counting procedure made explicit.",
    "topic": "Derivation of 73% figure"
  }
]
